<HEADLINE>
<P>
CRITIC'S PICK: 'THE OX' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Kevin Thomas 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 This flawless 1991 Swedish film of strength and calm marks the solo 
directorial debut of cinematographer Sven Nykvist and centers on the dire 
consequences facing a young tenant farmer (Stellan Skarsgard) after he slays an 
ox belonging to his employer in order to feed his starving family. An Oscar 
nominee for best foreign film, it is a spiritual odyssey, a study of the 
psychology of guilt and a period piece depicting hardship amid the most 
beautiful of settings.It is also a love story, an affirmation of the power of 
faith in the face of cruel injustice. Based on an actual incident, the film is 
set in 1867. Starring Liv Ullmann and Max von Sydow. (Bravo Monday at 5 p.m., 
again at 11 p.m.) Kevin Thomas 
</P>
</TEXT>
