<HEADLINE>
<P>
GUMP GRUMPS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Regarding "Forrest Gump's Proud Dad" (Aug. 7), "Gump Happens," the current ad 
line for "Forrest Gump," pretty much sums up my own opinion of the film, and I 
have no desire to step in it again -- especially not the sequel referred to in 
Robert Epstein's Film Clips Q&A with Gump author Winston Groom. 
</P>
<P>
 As a matter of fact, I have no desire to read the book upon which the film is 
based, nor do I wish to hear Mr. Groom reading it.Furthermore, if there are any 
Gump T-shirts and baseball caps anticipated, count me out on those as well. 
</P>
<P>
 JOHN P. STEVENS 
</P>
<P>
 Huntington Beach 
</P>
<P>
 I read "Forrest Gump's Proud Dad" with some concern. I'm sure the movie is as 
good as everyone is saying, but the nagging parallels to the book/movie "Being 
There" unsettle me. 
</P>
<P>
 Now I read about Paramount's brainstorm: Put out a quickie book of aphorisms 
called "Gumpisms: The Wit and Wisdom of Forrest Gump." This is too much! 
</P>
<P>
 Doesn't anyone remember a pamphlet that author/screenwriter Jerzy Kosinski 
issued to commemorate "Being There"? Probably not. It was called the 
"Quotations of Chauncey Gardiner,"illustrating the witty aphorisms of Chance, 
who (as the pamphlet states) has actually gone on to become President of the 
U.S.! 
</P>
<P>
 TOM DANKIEWICZ 
</P>
<P>
 San Gabriel 
</P>
