<HEADLINE>
<P>
YOUR MORTGAGE; PORTFOLIO LENDERS CAN FILL UNUSUAL NEEDS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DIAN HYMER, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 What are the pros and cons of using a portfolio lender? 
</P>
<P>
 A portfolio lender generates home loans that will become a part of that 
lender's own investment portfolio. This is in contrast to lenders who generate 
loans that are later sold to other investors. 
</P>
<P>
 Lenders who sell their loans usually sell them on the secondary money market 
to Fannie Mae (Federal National Mortgage Assn.) or Freddie Mac (Federal Home 
Loan Mortgage Corp.), two organizations that purchase home loans at a discount 
to resell to investors. Loans that are intended for sale to Freddie Mac or 
Fannie Mae must conform with rigid guidelines. Consequently, you'll find it 
harder to qualify for these loans. 
</P>
<P>
 Portfolio lenders usually have more flexibility in qualifying borrowers. For 
example, Freddie Mac and Fannie Mae won't permit all of the down payment to be 
a gift if the borrower is applying for a 90% loan. Some portfolio lenders, such 
as Great Western Bank, will permit all the down payment money to be a gift from 
parents or grandparents on a 90% loan. 
</P>
<P>
 Portfolio lenders may be able to stretch the qualifying ratios if your income 
is shy of what would be required for a Freddie Mac or Fannie Mae loan. 
</P>
<P>
 Your qualifying ratio is determined by dividing your monthly housing expense 
(which is the total of your loan payment, property taxes, hazard insurance, 
mortgage insurance and homeowner association fees, where applicable) by your 
gross monthly income. 
</P>
<P>
 For a Freddie Mac or Fannie Mae loan, this ratio shouldn't exceed 30% to 33%. 
A portfolio lender might allow a 40%, 50% or even 60% ratio, depending on how 
much cash you have to put down and if your credit rating is superb. 
</P>
<P>
 Portfolio lenders are not only more flexible in approving borrowers, they also 
have more latitude in approving property condition. A portfolio lender might be 
your only option if you need an "as is" loan to buy a property in its present 
condition. Some portfolio lenders will allow funds from the seller's proceeds 
to be held in an account so that termite or other repair work can be completed 
after closing. Freddie Mac and Fannie Mae loans won't permit holdbacks for such 
work. 
</P>
<P>
 First-Time Tip: Although portfolio lenders can work wonders for borrowers 
whose home purchase circumstances are out of the ordinary, this will not always 
be the case. Some portfolio lenders are enormous financial organizations with 
centralized loan origination operations. In some cases, this means less rather 
than more flexibility. 
</P>
<P>
 Before submitting a loan application with a portfolio lender, sit down with a 
loan agent and review your particular home loan needs. Find out if the loan 
processing and underwriting will be completed by local people knowledgeable 
about local conditions or if it'll be handled elsewhere. 
</P>
<P>
 One disadvantage of using portfolio lenders is that they usually offer a 
limited number of loan programs. If you don't qualify for the one you apply 
for, you may be out of luck. Mortgage brokers, on the other hand, usually have 
access to a multitude of programs and they can switch you from one to another 
quickly if you happen to be denied your loan of choice. 
</P>
<P>
 The Closing: Portfolio lenders often don't charge a separate appraisal fee. 
From time to time they offer promotional deals to stimulate business: A coupon 
for several hundred dollars off your loan origination fee, a free month's 
mortgage payment or an initial interest rate on an adjustable rate mortgage 
that no one else can match. Keep a lookout for such deals in the coming months 
as competition for your purchase home loan business intensifies. 
</P>
<P>
 Distributed by Inman News Features  
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
