<HEADLINE>
<P>
YEAR-ROUND BONUSES OF CONTAINER GARDENING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Container gardening offers year-round bonuses to the inventive gardener. 
Indoors or out, month in and month out, gardeners can derive pleasure from the 
plants they pots. 
</P>
<P>
 There are many advantages to growing plants in small containers, which can be 
moved at whim to take advantage of bloom color where it's needed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA082894-0212 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 073965 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
August 28, 1994, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Real Estate; Part K; Page 7; Column 6; Real Estate Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
121 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
GARDENER'S CHECKLIST 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 For dedicated gardeners, here are suggestions from the California Assn. of 
Nurserymen on what to do in the garden this week:  
</P>
<P>
 * Divide crowded clumps of Shasta daisies now for better flower size next 
summer. 
</P>
<P>
 * If your azaleas have set their buds switch to 0-10-10 fertilizer to promote 
bigger flowers in the spring. Using a high nitrogen fertilizer will cause the 
azaleas to drop their flower buds and keep on growing. 
</P>
<P>
 * Support chrysanthemums by staking. The fuller they become the greater the 
possibility they may break. 
</P>
<P>
 * Keep baiting slugs and snails especially once you've set out new seedlings. 
</P>
<P>
 * Water Japanese Iris thoroughly before and during the blooming season to 
promote a spectacular bloom. 
</P>
</TEXT>
