<HEADLINE>
<P>
WORLD IN BRIEF; LITHUANIA; LOW TURNOUT DOOMS ECONOMIC PROPOSAL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A referendum on compensating citizens for suffering caused by the switch to a 
market economy failed because the voter turnout was too low.International 
economists had said approval of the referendum, which was opposed by the 
reformed Communist government and backed by the opposition, would be 
catastrophic for the Baltic nation. The Central Elections Center reported that 
only 35% of voters had cast ballots just before polls closed. More than half of 
registered voters needed to take part for the referendum to be valid. 
</P>
